# Adventure conventions

An Adventure is a story arc the party runs inside this campaign. May be a published module (e.g. *Curse of Strahd*) or homebrew. Each adventure is its own directory under `adventures/`.

Avoid: "module" (reserve for *published* adventures only), "arc," "quest."

## Directory structure

```
adventures/<name>/
├── adventure.md          # the adventure's own page: frontmatter + prose
├── <scene-or-chapter>.md # optional subordinate notes
└── ...
```

- `<name>` is a slug (lowercase, hyphenated). Match the human-facing title closely so `[[wiki links]]` resolve naturally (e.g. `adventures/curse-of-strahd/` for *Curse of Strahd*).
- `adventure.md` is the canonical page for the adventure. Other markdown files in the directory are subordinate (chapters, scenes, locations bound to the adventure).
- NPCs, locations, factions, and items introduced by the adventure live in the campaign's top-level `npcs/`, `locations/`, `factions/`, `items/` directories — not nested under the adventure. The adventure references them via `[[wiki links]]`; backlinks tell you which adventure introduced or uses them.

## Frontmatter schema

`adventure.md` carries frontmatter that drives queries and the campaign overview. Required and optional fields:

```yaml
---
status: introduced                   # required: introduced | active | completed | abandoned
order: 3                             # ingest-era only: reliable GM-supplied sequence
introduced: ~                        # real-world date; null when unknown
started: ~                           # real-world date; null when unknown
completed: ~                         # real-world date; null when unknown
in_world_duration: ~                 # optional, free-form prose (e.g. "3 in-game months")
real_world_duration: ~               # optional, free-form prose (e.g. "~6 sessions")
---
```

- `status` is the only universally-required field.
- `order` is meaningful for **ingest-era** adventures (history the GM is importing without precise dates). For **session-tracked** adventures (started after the campaign was scaffolded), `order` is unnecessary — sequence is derivable from `started`.
- Dates are real-world dates. Use `~` (YAML null) when unknown. The agent never asks the GM to invent dates.
- Durations are narrative annotations. Treat as prose, not structured time. Use whichever axis the GM remembers; both are optional.

## Status transitions

```
introduced  ──►  active  ──►  completed
                   │
                   └────►  abandoned
```

- **`introduced`** — the adventure exists in this campaign's history but the party hasn't begun running it yet. (Or, for ingest-era history, it's a placeholder until the GM confirms it started.)
- **`active`** — the party is currently running this adventure. Sets `started` (or carries an ingest-era null).
- **`completed`** — finished, resolved. Sets `completed` date.
- **`abandoned`** — the party walked away or the GM dropped it. Status persists as historical record; sets `completed` date with `abandoned` semantics.

`/wrap-session` proposes status transitions based on `notes.md` content; the GM approves them as part of the wrap review. Don't change status outside the wrap workflow without a deliberate reason.

## Multiple active adventures

A campaign may have more than one `status: active` adventure at a time. Briefs surface all active adventures; the campaign overview lists them.

## Linking

Reference an adventure from anywhere via `[[Adventure Name]]` (matching `adventure.md` title or the directory slug). Beats scoped to an adventure use `[[wiki links]]` from the Beat to the adventure (or vice versa); backlinks resolve scoping at query time.
